text:
today marks three years since i was raped. i didn‚Äôt realize that until midway through the morning, which is significant, and i‚Äôve talked about my own experience with sexual assault a lot, so i‚Äôm going to talk about something different; what happened to me is not unique. it‚Äôs not rare, or abnormal, or an outlier. my story is one of many, each with their own gut-wrenching details, their own long battles back, and what makes these stories so powerful is that there are so fucking many of them.
.
1 in 4. 1 in 6. for men the statistics range from 1 in 33 to 1 in 70, and it‚Äôs probably much more than that; for every ten rape survivors, there is one man.
.
these numbers increase for people who are marginalized; 49% of multiracial women, 45% of native american women, and over 20% have been the victims of sexual violence; 1 in 2 trans people have been sexually assaulted.
.
1 in 4 girls and 1 in 6 boys will be the victims of sexual contact before they turn eighteen.
.
30% of women who have been sexually assaulted will show signs of ptsd for more than nine months after the assault.
.
the cost of being raped is about $130,000.
.
my story is a very old and awful one. it is not unique. look around next time you‚Äôre in a room with other people, and count out groups of four women. think of your friends, your classmates, your family. groups of four. how many of them have had to bear something unbearable? how many of them have their own awful story?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢
#sexualassault #survivors #1in4 #metoo #metoomovement

text:
i constantly get women message me, wanting to start their own business, but not having the confidence in themselves to 'just say yes'! they tell me they're not inspiring, they don't know enough people, they don't have time, etc etc. üôà

when i look back before i started my business, i didn‚Äôt have many close friends. i rarely posted on facebook and when i did it was mainly doom and gloom! üò≥ (the cringe of looking at my ‚Äòmemories‚Äô üòÇ) the beauty of this business is you learn as you go along, i'm still learning and people who have done this a lot longer than me still learn new things! you make new friends as you go and you have so much fun doing it that you will make the time for it! 
i rarely write long winded posts... but i just needed to get it off my chest. have some faith in yourselves and you can achieve anything you put your mind to. look at donald trump! üòÇ

text:
hi. this is me. this is another photo of me screaming at the world, acting touch, climbing uphill, concuring the elements. people (read: men) often ask me why i become so passionate when i talk about being a woman in this world, or when i write shows about female heroes in history like kenau, iphigeneia or margaret hughes. ‚Äòwhy are you so angry? go get married, have some kids and shut up! smile, girl, you‚Äôre far too pretty to be angry.‚Äô i‚Äôm not angry in this picture. i‚Äôm just showing my teeth. why? because i have to. why? because even a spoilt, entitled, privileged uptown white girl like me has had her #metoo moments and has to fight to be taken seriously in business or has to answer for the fact that she travels alone, goes to bars alone, drinks pints of black beer and didn‚Äôt start a family yet. so sometimes girls like me have to pound our chest like a gorilla and show our teeth to show the world that the fact that we don‚Äôt fit into a box doesn‚Äôt mean that we are freaks. last week a date asked if i was sure i wasn‚Äôt gay because i was so different from all the women he knew. what is gender anyway? 
this post isn‚Äôt about me. the most impressive moment in my trip to scotland was watching hannah gadsby‚Äôs show on netflix. watch it. it‚Äôs important. this woman will change the way you look at the world. at women. at gender. at being gay. it will change the way you raise your children and it will help you understand that we, as people, have to do a better job at understanding each other and allowing everybody be who they are, no more labels, no more phobia, no more boxes. it will show you an amazing, inspiring, strong, vulnarable, angry woman who has been broken and who has built herself up again. it will hit you like a ton of bricks. it will open your eyes. my sister has been asking me to watch it for weeks and i was ‚Äòtoo busy‚Äô watching a stupid netflix show. no excuses. watch it. 
and us women: let‚Äôs show our teeth when we need to, but also be kind and empowering towards each other. let everybody love who they want to love and identify with whatever gender and let‚Äôs lift each other up instead of putting each other down. we still have a long way to go.

text:
el silbato como arma femenina contra el acoso sexual, una idea surgida hace dos a√±os en la capital de m√©xico, ha dado el salto hasta marruecos, donde un grupo de activistas repartieron hoy cerca de 10.000 silbatos por todo el pa√≠s para animar a las mujeres a silbar ante cada caso de ataque.

la versi√≥n marroqu√≠ del #metoo se llama #masaktach (no me callo) y surgi√≥ hace unos meses en las redes sociales. son sus activistas las que hoy se lanzaron a las calles de todo el pa√≠s para repartir los silbatos con el lema ‚Äúsi se sobrepasa, pita‚Äù. ‚Äúno se trata de una manifestaci√≥n ni de una marcha‚Äù, dijo a efe una de las fundadoras del movimiento, leyla slassi, sino de sensibilizar y ‚Äúliteralmente hacer ruido‚Äù para atajar un fen√≥meno que ‚Äúest√° ah√≠, en todo momento y en todo lugar‚Äù. las transe√∫ntes que hoy eran abordadas en las avenidas c√©ntricas de rabat mostraban en un principio su sorpresa ante el inesperado ‚Äúregalo‚Äù de un silbato, y se lo tomaban en un principio a broma, hasta que, tras una breve conversaci√≥n, entend√≠an la filosof√≠a de la acci√≥n y aceptaban llevarse su silbato.

uno de los mensajes que repet√≠an las activistas era la propia ley 503-1-1 del c√≥digo penal marroqu√≠, que castiga con penas de entre uno y seis meses de c√°rcel m√°s una multa a quien practique el acoso ‚Äúen espacios p√∫blicos y otros con actos, palabras y gestos de car√°cter sexual o con fines sexuales‚Äù. la ley, que acaba de aprobarse recientemente, ha tenido un recorrido hasta ahora discreto, y el primer juicio celebrado en la ciudad de fez contra un acosador para aplicarle esa nueva ley acab√≥ en nada, pues la v√≠ctima retir√≥ su denuncia ante la atenci√≥n medi√°tica levantada por el caso.

el movimiento feminista lamenta que esa ley, pese a su contenido positivo, no contemple mecanismos concretos que hagan m√°s f√°ciles las denuncias, ni tampoco incluya sensibilizaci√≥n entre los polic√≠as y los jueces, encargados de aplicar esa ley.

text:
grateful to have spoken at the #metoo event as a latinx transmasculine sexual abuse survivor. 
i first experienced sexual abuse at 13, i would wear baggy clothes to hide my unwanted puberty changes. an adult (white cis man) took advantage of my dysphoria and befriended me and then took advantage of the situation. he forced me to do things i couldn‚Äôt comprehend, that made me feel dirty. his excuse was that he was curious to see what my ‚Äútrue ‚Äú sex was under my baggy clothes. 
the next time was when i was 18, i had started my self discovery journey to transition, had cut my hair and started dressing more masculine,  i was sexually harassed by an intoxicated man, who told me i was too ‚Äúpretty‚Äù to dress like a boy, that i needed to try boys, then went on to call me names. this was on a metro bus with a lot of people, yet not one spoke up. he then went on to get off the bus on my stop and stalk me until i went to a coffee shop to wait it out. 
i spoke up at this event, to offer a voice in the trans community who faces the most abuse. 
in fact ‚Äúone in two transgender individuals are sexually abused or assaulted at some point in their lives. some reports estimate that transgender survivors may experience rates of sexual assault up to 66 percent, often coupled with physical assaults or abuse.‚Äù i am visible for those that cannot be, i am visible so that my trans siblings know that they are not alone.

slacktivism: are we lazy?
as you are reading this post, a politician is calling us lazy. there is evidence of gen-z and millennials being the age gap that votes the least! a term called slacktivism has been coined to describe our actions or rather lack thereof. we [internet-users] receive our news through social media platforms and repost pressing issues through hashtag activism. by doing so, we can get these topics trending globally and raise awareness to issues that affect our daily lives. our participation does matter, whether it be online or voting. this stigma has been present in our generation, but we can utilize these powerful digital tools in order to create change. #youmatter

text: been starting holiday shopping early this year & when necessary hiding it with a danger dragon on guard [aka tiny snek, mercury] for morgan‚Äôs pressies. because my teenager is wicked smart & will find them. i try to leave magic in this & thusly, my local artisan haunts in the day to day allow for the gradual ease & enjoyment. it‚Äôs been years that the shopping season hasn‚Äôt completely repulsed me & i steer clear of it. that sometimes spills into the mood overall & coupled with history - i dread holidays. time heals & as we make clear of that - we make new traditions. one, is in what we spend on & where. i‚Äôve always been a creator & gifted from this, but it‚Äôs a great addition in the community of online artists through fb & ig. it‚Äôs important to support each other & our good vibe tribes (s.o., smallish bears, birdos, cattos & doggos). i‚Äôm proud of my artist friends who work into the ether to hone their craft & survive on their wares. it‚Äôs not an easy choice & the tax changes this year are gonna be brutal. keep going. i am grateful that i can trade work, have the time for commissions that mean a great deal to them & in the creation of to me, too. a huge contrast to how i felt under corporate pressured rules of financial benefit over those we served. i sleep better at night & that this is carried into my choices for this season, as it should; reciprocal in the spirit of giving. a palpable energy in this; it‚Äôs a web that i can connect to. it grounds me in what is important when the world feels anything but & it gives me hope in today & for tomorrow. i learned today of how this is not limited to these walls. this tee from @billsafi is mine. üòçi wore it out shopping today, & i began to make note of people smiling at me - which is nice, but why? i happened to catch the gaze of a woman in line & then i got it. i am gonna say it - i looked for it after. wonders of positivity in the following places/peoples especially the faces of women reading it & the smile grow when it hit home. best part of art. ‚ò∫Ô∏è‚ú®my 2 favorite ladysmiths are around my neck (every day)turquoise ‚Äòancestors‚Äô skull by @floraandfauuna & the ‚Äòevil eye monocle‚Äô by @flannerygrace

text:
@regrann from @thedailyember - now with the progressives we elected, lets stop selling weapons to saudi arabia.
.
.
‚Äúwashington (ap) ‚Äî the united states will stop refueling saudi arabian aircraft fighting houthi rebels in yemen, the pentagon and the saudi kingdom said late friday.

the refueling change does not affect the u.s. military assistance and training to improve the saudi airstrikes, which have reportedly caused thousands of civilian deaths. ‚Äúthe u.s. and the coalition are planning to collaborate on building up legitimate yemeni forces to defend the yemeni people, secure their country‚Äôs borders, and contribute to counter al-qaida and isis efforts in yemen and the region,‚Äù u.s. defense secretary jim mattis said.

as a result, the decision to halt the u.s. refueling will likely have little impact on the fight, but will allow the trump administration to say it has taken action against the saudis for the devastation in yemen.

the saudi statement said it had ‚Äúincreased its capability to independently conduct inflight refueling,‚Äù and therefore ‚Äúrequested cessation of inflight refueling support for its operations in yemen.‚Äù the action comes amid growing congressional anger against saudi arabia, a key ally and the country where president donald trump made his first visit abroad after taking office.‚Äù
via @apnews

text:
now with the progressives we elected, lets stop selling weapons to saudi arabia.
.
.
‚Äúwashington (ap) ‚Äî the united states will stop refueling saudi arabian aircraft fighting houthi rebels in yemen, the pentagon and the saudi kingdom said late friday.

the refueling change does not affect the u.s. military assistance and training to improve the saudi airstrikes, which have reportedly caused thousands of civilian deaths. ‚Äúthe u.s. and the coalition are planning to collaborate on building up legitimate yemeni forces to defend the yemeni people, secure their country‚Äôs borders, and contribute to counter al-qaida and isis efforts in yemen and the region,‚Äù u.s. defense secretary jim mattis said.

as a result, the decision to halt the u.s. refueling will likely have little impact on the fight, but will allow the trump administration to say it has taken action against the saudis for the devastation in yemen.

my sport gave me so many immeasurable opportunities. i have a bachelors and masters degree completely debt free, i have traveled to and trained in three different countries, competed in almost all 50 states, and have a resume filled with characteristics that make me a stand out applicant. but the sport also shaped me into the perfect victim - the silent survivor. it taught me that deviations from perfection are unacceptable. that  appearance sometimes matters more than skill. and that power and authority trump morals and comfort. .
.
my story traces every step of what molded me into the perfect victim for larry nassar. how gymnastics created an environment where silence was easier than the pain and discomfort. my book demands change. .
.
.

text:
not inktober, day 11

veterans day, 2018 
america,

we have wronged so many people. we have wronged ourselves and one another. we have shown hatred, and we have denied ourselves.

the death of a person by another man's hand is not only a tremendous loss of life; it's also signifies the loss of our humanity. 
we must be aware of what we are capable of in order to be sensitive. what good is communicating without the ability to listen? if we disagree, not knowing how to communicate can become destructive. 
if we can have the patience to speak, to mediate rather than to dictate, we might not come to an immediate agreement, but we will at least see that we are trying. it means more than buying time.

how do we make the best of what we have? what does it mean to move forward? 
stronger together.

love, üåò

text:
who would've thought, all those years ago when i was a youngster of 19, that i would be running ultra marathons and climbing summits in the italian alps when i was 48. 
not me. 
i didn't think i was 'sporty'. without even realising it i had put myself into a box. categorised myself as one thing, not another. 
the 'brainy one' of the family. so then clearly not the sporty one. 
yet nobody told me that. 
at some young age i just assumed it about myself. 
how often do you put yourself into a box? 
unconsciously limit who you are,  and what you might like to do, by default? 
not based on your talents. not based on your experiences. 
but based on an unspoken, unconscious belief that if you are 'this' then you must not be'that'? because 'that' isn't compatible with 'this'. the hell it's not. 
don't be put in a box. 
least of all by yourself. 
i still have that dress from when i was 19. it was my mother's. 
a fond reminder for that 19 year old how far she has come, grown and expanded (a little too much to still fit the dress üòÜüòú) nearly 30 years later. 
look back darling. 
how far have you come? 
what are you doing now that you didn't realise you could accomplish? 
the best thing is... it's not over! 
you can keep discovering until your last breath. 
#youaremorethanyouimagine #youneverknow #youneverknowuntilyoutry #listentoyourheart #letyourselfdream #thinkoutsidethebox #untameable #nothingsimpossible

text:
oh hey! surviving me has its commercial release today on www.sectionii.com! $1 of every purchase goes to the nonprofit @morethanmeorg which builds schools for girls in liberia. 
surviving me was made by women pictured is composer liz lysinger (left), actor mira furlan (center), and writer-director leah yananton (right) at our world premiere at the arclight hollywood in the hollywood film festival. www.sectionii.com is also a platform by and for women & #lgbtq filmmakers & audiences. 
surviving me: the nine circles of sophie (105 min) written & directed by #leahyananton stars #mirafurlan (lost), #vincentpiazza (boardwalk empire), #fredriclehne (greatest showman) and #christineryndak as sophie. 
as she enters her junior year of college, aspiring poet sophie (christine ryndak) embarks on a journey of self-discovery with her friends jimmy (vincent piazza) and kiera (leah yananton), but her moral compass is challenged while she‚Äôs trying to study and find a way to pay for her college expenses. as financial and peer pressures suffocate and literally starve sophie, her intellectual mentor, professor slateman (fredric lehne), provides a ray of hope. meanwhile, slateman‚Äôs wife, jacqueline slateman (mira furlan) seems to take her husband‚Äôs pupil under her wing, further increasing sophie‚Äôs sense of confusion. sophie‚Äôs eventual choices lead her deeper into dante‚Äôs inferno ending with horrific repercussions. but was she to blame? 
surviving me features a brave, luminous performance by newcomer christine ryndak as a young woman awakening to her sexual identity and accepting the weight of accountability as she navigates the ‚Äúinferno‚Äù of sex and love in college. first time filmmaker leah yananton cleverly interweaves poetry and text throughout the story, mirroring sophie‚Äôs internal and external struggles.

text:
have you ever asked yourself how you needed to dress up in the morning ? ‚†Ä
‚†Ä
no, not how you wanted to dress up. 
how you needed to dress up. 
i have. 
do you know why ? 
because we live in a world where 100% of women have been a victim of street harassment.
and you know the worst part ? 
we blame women for it. 
we tell them they should not have provoked him. 
when all they are guilty of, was wearing an outfit they liked. 
the outfit is not even the problem. 
i have been harassed wearing a skirt. 
i have also been harassed wearing a huge sweater & a tracksuit. 
we don‚Äôt need to change. 
men need to behave ‚úãüèº

text:
we finished the full translation of the so film france interview with rob. as it is quite lengthy we will post it in nine parts. part 9, the last one, is about change. swipe through the next (2) pages to read the full answers.

about change in hollywood: "already people around me are often talking about the metoo movement. within the film business everyone is trying to reach other audiences and now that there are more channels where we can broadcast what we are creating, it extends the spectrum of the kinds of projects that can be realized." about change in london: "i do not remember the last time someone told me he was a poet. it did not happen anymore, but it comes back. so i will go to open mic poetry nights." thanks to our affiliate pattinson art work and @/robspromo twitter for helping with the translations. it would not have been possible without you girls!

text:
how fine is the line between self love and narcissism? is there even a line? 
today was a perfectly normal day. brushing my teeth, doing some homework, checking my phone a couple of times. at around 1:30, i decided that i wanted to go out. after doing my makeup, i looked in the mirror. i thought i looked pretty good. is there anything wrong with that? no. there is a huge gap between self love and narcissism. a person can think they're beautiful without making them narsisstic. self love is so important and it shows that you actually care about yourself. so if you ever find yourself loving how you look, don't ever feel ashamed of it. because you do look beautiful. it's a fact. so there's nothing wrong with thinking that
.
.
.
don't forget to vote in my story! i'd love to know what you think about this
.
.
.
i feel beautiful by fantasia barrino
.
.
.

how fine is the line between self love and narcissism? is there even a line? 
today was a perfectly normal day. brushing my teeth, doing some homework, checking my phone a couple of times. at around 1:30, i decided that i wanted to go out. after doing my makeup, i looked in the mirror. i thought i looked pretty good. is there anything wrong with that? no. there is a huge gap between self love and narcissism. a person can think they're beautiful without making them narsisstic. self love is so impoant and it shows that you actually care about yourself. so if you ever find yourself loving how you look, do not ever feel ashamed of it. because you do look beautiful. it is a fact. so there's nothing wrong with thinking that
.
.
.
do not forget to vote in my story! i'd love to know what you think about this
.
.
.
i feel beautiful by fantasia barrino
.
.
.

text:
#minggunercerita edisi 11 november 2018

selepas magrib, beberapa perempuan berkumpul membahas soal berita "kontroversional" yang dikeluarkan oleh balairung, pers mahasiswa ugm. "kenapa coba si agni itu keluar malem-malem sendirian, kan bisa nunggu sampai pagi?" "kenapa waktu dua pemuda itu pulang dia ngga minta tolong dianterin aja dan malah milih buat nginep?" "kenapa waktu si hs meluk dia ngga teriak? kenapa harus 'nunggu' dulu?" itu segelintir komentar mereka mengenai kasus agni. 
di satu sisi ada 'keributan' yang terjadi di bawah postingan di line, identitas hs tersebar luas, nama asli, jurusan, nim bahkan hingga nomor orang tua. "sebarin aja informasi soal hs biar dia kapok, ngga malu apa" "kurang ajar, ngga punya otak"

dan berbagai komentar lain soal hs.

kemudian bermunculan berbagai tulisan menanggapi berita agni, mulai dari dukungan atas keberanian agni untuk menceritakan kasusnya, penjelasan mengenai "kenapa agni diem aja pas dipeluk hs", ajakan untuk tidak melakukan persekusi kepada hs, komentar soal sedetail apa harusnya sebuah kasus bisa ditulis oleh media massa, hingga petisi agar ugm mengusut tuntas kasus ini sampai selesai. 
sangat disayangkan bahwa masih ada orang yang menggunakan "namanya juga kucing, dikasih ikan mana nolak" untuk menanggapi kasus ini. 
penggunaan perumpamaan ini jelas salah karena pertama, tidak semua kucing doyan ikan. banyak kucing rumahan yang sejak awal diberi makan makanan kucing sekelas whiskas sehingga tidak tertarik untuk menyentuh ikan. kedua, manusia bukan kucing. mereka punya akal sehat yang membantu untuk memutuskan tindakan mana yang benar dan yang salah. menyamakan manusia dengan kucing sama saja dengan menghina manusia itu sendiri sekaligus menghina tuhan yang telah menciptakan manusia dengan sebaik-baiknya. 
melihat hal ini, pendidikan mengenai gender menjadi penting untuk memanusiakan manusia dan mencegah munculnya pemikiran bahwa si a menjadi superior, dominan daripada si b karena perbedaan gender.

semoga ugm segera menyelesaikan masalah ini sehingga agni mendapatkan haknya dan hs merasakan akibat dari perbuatannya. semoga materi gender segera masuk dalam kurikulum pendidikan di indonesia.

text:
outside the matrix : the salt of the earth

matthew 5:13-16
13¬†‚Äúyou are the salt of the earth. but if the salt loses its saltiness, how can it be made salty again?

the scripture says you are the salt of the earth. salt is most commonly used to flavor foods. it can overpower the taste of whatever food it is applied to. in terms of the scripture it means our culture is the salt of the earth. african american culture sets trends all over the world. i will focus on music not sports.

like a kitty licking bulldagger that mimics the negative traits of masculinity, these nations do the same. for example, dykes will dress as men but act like the thug men, sagging their pants, talking slow and cool and getting tats.

you rarely see dykes perpetrate the positive aspects of masculinity, because they only mimick what is pushed on them visibly. the other nations do the same thing, they will mimick the thug image of blacks, not the positive images, because they aren't shown that on their televisions.

this is why the scripture says "but if the salt loses its saltiness, how can it be made salty again", because  we are showing the negative examples. the reality is the history of our people are a righteous people, of great character, great morales and great spirituality. we once were the salt of the heart showing the world righteousness, science and discipline.

hence the common white shaming tactic "we wuz kangz". america has portrayed black men as "thugs and rappers" for generations. so much to the point that urban clothing, tattoos, baggy clothes, cars with big rims, gold teeth and most importantly hip hop/rap is what many people associate blacks with.

when you look at these other nations, they are mimicking the same "culture" that we were demonized with.

when you look at these clips, understand these are smaller examples of larger communities in those countries.

we can go to most countries, in europe, asia and african and see people perpetrating so called "black urban culture". can we go into any predominately black area in america and see black men acting, speaking, dressing or mimicking music and cultures from india, china, japan, korea, pakistan, saudis?

the play portrays a world which is deeply correlated with the the #metoo movement!

there is no dialogue, nor text in this play. it traspases¬† language¬† barriers in such a way that any person from any country can understand it, given its universal codes.

text:
comfort women were women and girls forced into sexual slavery by the imperial japanese army in occupied territories before and during world war¬†ii

acknowledging and prosecuting those responsible is required, but¬†so are full and effective reparations for victims and comprehensive reforms to address the discrimination against women and girls in society that underpins the crimes.

providing justice for the survivors of the military sexual slavery matters not only as a moral obligation but for what it says about our society now and in the future. addressing these past human rights violations will contribute to improving the situation of women and minorities today as well help stop any repetition of these abhorrent crimes.

text_retweet:
#repost @facesofbengaluru "i knew of his family‚Äô practices.  he had once justified beating women by saying, ‚Äòif a woman doesn‚Äôt listen to her husband, it is okay to hit her. even my father hits my mother when she does mistakes. in fact, a man is mean only when he‚Äôs truly in love.‚Äô he was extremely influenced by cinema. he thought behaving like a goon, made him ‚Äòheroic‚Äô. he‚Äôd say it aloud, ‚Äòyes i‚Äôm a bad guy, yes i‚Äôm psycho, yes i will hurt you, but that‚Äôs because i love you.‚Äô"
.
"this one time on my 18th birthday, my friends and he surprised me. it was at that studio bar in orion mall. they were all drinking and my best friend obviously asked me to drink. i hadn‚Äôt drank before. he too passed a glass with a smile. and he suddenly turned to me, his smile flattened into a line and he said under his breath, ‚Äòif you touch it, you‚Äôre dead‚Äô. and then he pretended to be a jovial guy when he turned towards the others. that was my first encounter with the psycho in him."
.
‚Äúi thought of leaving him several times as i was losing my sanity. but he‚Äôd convinced me that now that he‚Äôd touched me, i wasn‚Äôt ‚Äòpure‚Äô and that nobody would marry me. i was naive. i was scared that i‚Äôd end up alone. i eventually broke up with him and now i‚Äôm in love with a gentleman who makes my world a happy place.‚Äù
.
‚Äúi had a childhood filled with sexual abuse and trauma, just like most other women. i was flat-chested and skinny like every other 8 years old. i stayed at home to be safe. my cousin would come home and slide his hand under my skirt. so if someone asks you to cover and lock yourself in to stay safe, rub my story on their face.‚Äù
.
"it is common, but it does not make it alright. today i‚Äôm a writer. i write about abuse, shaming, gender inequality and several other issues. i stand up for men, women and people who recognize themselves with the gender of their liking. i am their voice.‚Äù
.
‚Äúi always told my mother i did not like my name. but now i‚Äôve come to realise that i have been named to know my purpose in life. i want to protect people. i want to be the person i missed having when i faced abuse. by being their voice, by standing by them and making sure no others go through the same.

text:
#boricuasbelike brilliant and #relentless. decolonial bizness world is a free and open method for business education that promotes reparations and decolonization. #reparations means repairing the damage that racism, capitalism, and settler colonialism have produced globally through formal, economic amends. #decolonization means creating open pathways for life to thrive on this planet as we move into the new sun. both reparations and decolonization involve abolishing borders and prisons and restoring the sacred connections between humans and the many other forms of life that live on this planet, earth, as we face #climatechaos, the #sixthextinction, and #proudfascism.

#decolonialbiznessworld is made for the magicians of the global economy, those of us who have been forced to the margins of capitalist accumulation, while serving its masters and everyday beneficiaries. we have been made marginal even as we remain the global majority. decolonial bizness world is also made for our allies, for people who see truth through delusion and violence and are willing to put their money where their mantra lives: on the books and into daily sacred practice.

first, there is no one method or formula for determining reparations.

so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience as individuals is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this earth walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and #metoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an economic and spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to foster healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the support we require to create solutions for ourselves and our beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to learn and apply the method?

from a purely economic perspective, what can financial reparations facilitate? #manifestation of #justicia y #sanaci√≥n.

so much of the violence we experience is personalized. the violence we experience as individuals is always shared by other people and communities, yet how it affects us is embodied and related to who we are in this eah walk. that's why this method was designed for people like you and etoo.

second, calculating reparations is always an economic and spiritual practice.

above all, the spiritual dimension of this method is central, and survivors must lead each initiative. the point is to foster healing, not pay for therapy and legal costs, and give people the suppo we require to create solutions for ourselves and our beloved communities. so, what does healing mean for you as a survivor of the violence you seek to stop? given your daily life and needs at this time, what do you need to put in place to learn and apply the method?

from a purely economic perspective, what can ficial reparations facilitate?  of  y

i fell hard for victoria james, sommelier and partner at cote in nyc, amid animals dangling over bonfires by a dry quarry at an¬†@heirloomfire event¬†@gathergreene. she was with her husband, wine importer @lyle railsback and i was with my husband¬†@barclaypalmer and daughter¬†@sylviepalmer. but that didn't prevent a fairly intense conversation about family, #metoo, challenges to young women coming up in the wine business, alcoholism, the way forward, ros√©, and writing. our conversation wandered, rambled, returned, but was always strikingly honesty and direct. victoria didn't scoot around hard topics. i invited her onto #speakingbroadly, so we could delve deeper into the topics we touched upon, including why she hates the word "tender" when it's used to describe young women in the restaurant business; ‚Äúit means they're young and fuckable." that comment kicked off a provocative interview with one of the country's most celebrated wine talents. listen in for more insights from @geturgrapeon. link in bio.

text:
from @michaelakiersch 
sexual assault and harassment is not only prevalent in the climbing community, it is overwhelmingly frequent. 
in a survey administered by #safeoutside, 1 in 3 participants reported to have experienced some form of sexual assault or harassment. of the women who answered, almost half (47.3%) indicated that they were a victim of some form of sexual misconduct. ‚Äúafter experiencing sexual harassment and assault, 45.4 percent of respondents‚Äîand 54.5 percent of women‚Äîsaid the incident changed the way they climb.‚Äù this is unacceptable. 
i have my own experience with this in the climbing community. sexual misconduct ranges from catcalling, inappropriate messages, to physical advances. i am not speaking only to those who commit these acts, also to victims, bystanders, and those who are simply unaware. educate yourselves, protect yourselves, and do the same with those in your community. 
we must do better together. link to the full article in my bio. #metoo

text:
"people often ask me why i sew.  when i was younger, i would have said i loved hearing people say ‚Äòi can‚Äôt believe you made that?‚Äô don‚Äôt get me wrong, i do still love to hear that, but recently i‚Äôve realised it plays a much more meaningful role in my life. a few weeks ago i tried on some clothes in a high-street shop for the first time in months and immediately i felt horrible. why didn‚Äôt i fit in the size i should? why doesn‚Äôt it look right? why doesn‚Äôt it look like how it does on the model? i got back to my trusty sewing machine and took a step back ‚Äì is it that i don‚Äôt fit into society‚Äôs expectations of women‚Äôs size? or is it more that there are unrealistic expectations about what women should look like? by sewing everything i wear whenever i can, i take back control ‚Äì the clothes are made to fit me, i don‚Äôt try to change my body to fit pre-conceived expectations. in years gone by, girls might have been forced to take sewing classes at school because they weren‚Äôt expected to pursue anything else. nowadays, i like to think that sewing is a symbol of empowerment and represents a community of creative women that i feel so grateful to be part of. instead of harshly commenting on each others‚Äô appearances, it‚Äôs overwhelmingly positive ‚Äì we applaud and support each other, recreational sewists and inspiring business owners alike." ‚Äî izzy üßµ

text:
each day i do at least one thing to work towards fulfilling my dream.  and each day i write in my gratitude journal one thing i am thankful for. today especially, i am extremely grateful to have positive news about my biopsy -  i‚Äôm all clear! today will definitely be a special entry in my journal!  i truly believe that everything that happens is all part of my journey.  i‚Äôm finding my purpose and it‚Äôs so exciting! 
each day is a gift. do something amazing today! even if you‚Äôre struggling through life right now there‚Äôs at least one thing you can be grateful for. acknowledge it and it will give you the strength you need to keep forging forward! you‚Äôre worth it!  xo

text:
i'm over on @feministsof today talking about sewing and feminism üòç have a read! „Éª„Éª„Éª
"people often ask me why i sew.  when i was younger, i would have said i loved hearing people say ‚Äòi can‚Äôt believe you made that?‚Äô don‚Äôt get me wrong, i do still love to hear that, but recently i‚Äôve realised it plays a much more meaningful role in my life. a few weeks ago i tried on some clothes in a high-street shop for the first time in months and immediately i felt horrible. why didn‚Äôt i fit in the size i should? why doesn‚Äôt it look right? why doesn‚Äôt it look like how it does on the model? i got back to my trusty sewing machine and took a step back ‚Äì is it that i don‚Äôt fit into society‚Äôs expectations of women‚Äôs size? or is it more that there are unrealistic expectations about what women should look like? by sewing everything i wear whenever i can, i take back control ‚Äì the clothes are made to fit me, i don‚Äôt try to change my body to fit pre-conceived expectations. in years gone by, girls might have been forced to take sewing classes at school because they weren‚Äôt expected to pursue anything else. nowadays, i like to think that sewing is a symbol of empowerment and represents a community of creative women that i feel so grateful to be part of. instead of harshly commenting on each others‚Äô appearances, it‚Äôs overwhelmingly positive ‚Äì we applaud and support each other, recreational sewists and inspiring business owners alike." ‚Äî izzy üßµ

training cannot simply comprise the dos and don‚Äôts, the what is and what is not acceptable workplace behaviour, to ensure everyone legally falls into line.

text:
next sunday 11.18, join us for a special event for sexual assault and harassment survivors. we are hosting a restorative justice healing circle to create a safe and sacred space in order to heal from these wounds. within the realm of restorative justice exists a practice called circle keeping which can be used for many reasons, such as building community, learning, peacemaking, healing and conflict transformation. 
a circle is co-created by all participants beginning with an opening ceremony and the construction of a centerpiece created with participants intentions and objects of meaning that have been brought to the circle. next, circle values and guidelines will be built by consensus followed by relationship and trust building involving the sharing of personal stories as sources of wisdom. we‚Äôll then move through some guiding questions that will begin to explore the feelings, concerns and issues as pre-determined by all participants from our previous relationship and trust building, working towards ways we can heal both individually and as a community. a talking piece is utilized to ensure boundaries for those who are speaking and those who are listening and a ceremony is used to close the circle.

our first circle is an opportunity to step into a safe environment, to express your experience should you choose, and to be listened to and held by the other members of the group. in a circle there is no debate, there is no judgement, there is only listening and collaboration via group consent. note, this is a survivor only circle.

the circle will be facilitated by valeria a. gheorghiu and andy izenson trained restorative justice circle facilitators and community uplifters. 3-5pm suggested $10 üíï #restorativejustice #healingcircle #healingtrauma #sexualassualt #sexualharassment #metoo #survivorstories #webelieve #healingtogether #healingeachother
name: Anahata Yoga & Healing Arts

text:
fifth poetry slam of my spoken word poetry series ~ rape 05

lose or thrive dead or alive i want to live not survive
rape is a big deal especially among female victims that should be treated with wisdom
far away from twisted systems
a controversy that leads to shitty policy
a sensitive subject that i will handle with intensive regret
simply explained; it‚Äôs having sex with her without her consent or after her disapprovement even if you are her husband
when you drug her rape her and pretend you didn‚Äôt hear her disagree
when she didn‚Äôt get a chance to interfere?
isn‚Äôt she free?
what about powerful rape when they step on the rules and take us for fools

in the #metoo era, there are exceptional examples of corporate leadership like ikea switzerland. its code of conduct is widely disseminated among employees, and it openly admits cases of sexual harassment and has a proactive plan to address them.

text: good morning & happy sunday!! i wanted to take a moment to share a personal experience that has lead to my physical and emotional journey. i was in an abusive relationship on and off for two years. i have just come out of that relationship determined to rebuild my inner (and outter) strength. after surviving cancer and a very toxic relationship, there is a lot of work to be done. the challenge of recovering from a highly critical & abusive relationship is that, your inner dialogue over time becomes your abusers voice. telling you that you are not good enough, you are not worth loving, you are hard to love, you are wrong, you are not a good person. you don‚Äôt realize this is happening, but over time, it slowly transitions. eventually you recognize that inner voice belongs to your abuser, and you can recognize it is wrong. nevertheless, it is there and you are forced to listen to it. you hear it criticize you when you look in the mirror, when you make a mistake, when you face rejection, or in situations where you have to think critically. sometimes, it pipes up for no reason at all. it is there to fill you with self-doubt. what i have realized this week is that the more time that goes by without interaction with your abuser, the quieter that voice gets. the less you doubt and second guess yourself. the more confident you feel, and the more ways you recognize that you are in fact worth loving. i firmly believe that with time, my inner voice will be my own again. it will just take time and space. i urge you, to leave someone who is not good for your mental health. you only have one life and we never know when it will be cut short. you deserve a happy and fulfilling life with a partner who nurtures you and magnifies your strengths. god lifts you up with his righteous right hand, and so should your partner üíóüïäüôèüèªüôåüèª i hope this perspective touches anyone who is experiencing or recovering from abuse. you are so much stronger than anyone will give you credit for. i see you. i believe you. and i truly, truly believe you are worth loving üíó‚úåüèª #bbg #mentalhealthawareness #survivor #mentalhealth #depression #anxiety #positivevibes #metoo #selflove #bhfyp #health #wellness

text: #nicedrunkgirlsinbathrooms #womenhelpingwomen #womenlookingoutforwomen sadly i had a few nights where i was able to receive the kindness of strange women and bathrooms. i remember getting sick from having too much to drink one night and women i didn't even know making sure i was okay before i went back out. i always reciprocated and kind it didn't matter what the woman looked like how old she was what she was wearing i saw a woman potentially needing my help. i remember one night in particular at a concert there was a woman who passed out in the mini skirt in the balcony around a lot of guys her friends were kicked out for being drunk and i made a point to make sure security knew that she was by herself vulnerable and drunk. a lot of people were annoyed by her she was young just like i was once and my heart went out to her. i probably prevented her from being raped at night so sometimes when you see those annoying drunk women remember ladies we were once young too sometimes it happens let's look out for each other avoid the next #metoo

text:
it's finally uploaded!! the first ever episode of ptsd tv üòä

what is ptsd tv you ask?! ptsd tv is a place where you can get help on your healing journey from two people who have been in your shoes.

you can watch the 1st episode on youtube. 
we talk open and honestly about ptsd and all it entails. 
how it affected us as individuals and our relationship and how we were able to overcome it 100%

in this episode we're talking about something super important... how to stay positive even in the darkest of times.

this was a huge piece to our healing journey and we know it will help you greatly if you apply these 3 thing too... watch it on youtube: overcoming ptsd

even if you don't believe recovery is possible or that you can do it.. we're here for you and believe in you 100,000%

please reach out if you have any questions or need anything at all!

email me at:
kayleen@overcomingptsd.info

here for you always,
kayleen & brad (& shiloh)

text:
freedom & joy & life & happiness & love
.
here‚Äôs me last night feeling all those things going out with the hubs for a little early birthday celebration dinnerüíÉüèº
.
last night was also 6 years to the day that i was going out for the night to celebrate my birthday during my sophomore year of college; the night i was sexually assaulted.
.
every year i wonder how i‚Äôll feel on this day... what will i think about... will it be hard... oh goodness y‚Äôall my heart on this day this year is in a place i didn‚Äôt know it could beüôåüèª
.
i almost didn‚Äôt even realize the day it was until getting ready to go to dinner. i‚Äôm so focused on living today and all the exciting life things going on right now that i can‚Äôt even bother to let myself sit and play back that night.
.
that night took a lot from me: my confidence; my body; my control; my easy going self; my trust; my sleep; and my ‚Äúself‚Äù in the way i had always known myself to be.
.
but that night has also led to a life that has given me so much more than it took: an education in a field i love; a chance to find out who i am & who i really want to be; a husband who gives me a love unlike any other; a deeper relationship with christ to cling to; a greater passion & ability for living a life of adventure; i am the strongest i have ever been physically, mentally, & emotionally; and my relationship with me, and the love i have for myself, is at a place i used to only dream of it beingüñ§
.
.
the world can be cruel. bad things happen. evil can be enacted upon us at the hands of others. but evil will never win. .
to put it kindly, i still don‚Äôt have very nice feelings about the ‚Äúboy‚Äù who sexually assaulted me. but boy am i a firm believer that the person i have become as a byproduct of the fire i have fought through because of what he did is stronger, more powerful, more faith-full, more joyful, and dare i say more successful, than i used to imagine i would be as i am about to enter my 26th year.
.
my heart will not harden because of the evil others manifest in this world, but instead i will spread love and joy all the more freely in order to give others hope, strength, and a place to say #metoo ü§üüèª

text:
we have a lot to learn from each other. this #sunday we‚Äôre reading kate harding‚Äôs thought piece in why the intergenerational feminist divide over #metoo is both painful and necessary. here are some key takeaways:
.
.
‚Äúyoung feminists are pushing the growing movement deeper, causing older feminists to worry about preserving the progress we've already made.‚Äù
.
.
‚Äúfeminists of [the younger] generation and older have, for years, been accused of overreacting, of labeling every little touch ‚Äúsexual assault,‚Äù as we attempted to force society to grapple with the existence (let alone prosecutability) of acquaintance or "date" rape.‚Äù
.
.
‚Äúeven if they don't fully realize where it all came from, it's clear that today's young feminists have taken the anti-rape lessons of the second and third waves ‚Äî only yes means yes, coercion is not consent, consent can be withdrawn at any time ‚Äî very much to heart.‚Äù
.
.
read the full piece at the link in our bio.

repost from @soberfishie 
this basically sums it all up. this is absolutely the main reason for staying sober for me. 
my therapist started telling me about the dangers of alcohol in august 2016 and at first i didn't believe him. however everything he said made sense and he had not drank alcohol in 50 years. he never had a drinking problem, he just committed to yoga in 1967 when visiting @srf_lakeshrine in l.a.  he learned there how damaging it is to the mind body and spirit connection. eventually i entered treatment for alcohol abuse and learned more about how toxic alcohol is and since getting help have lost the desire to drink. i was lucky and got to spend time at the same self realization center in l.a. during treatment!

„Éª„Éª„Éª
we would like to invite you to come see our play today sunday at 3:00pm 
it is a experimental, avant garde and surreal performance. we use a combination of sounds, movement and music. citizens of the gray or this dark thing that sleeps in me is a theatrical production generated by the curiosity of how the relationship between man and woman has evolved throughout the years and how this relationship has become a struggle for power; a fight to death where there can be only one winner. 
the play portrays a world which is deeply correlated with the the #metoo movement!

there is no dialogue, nor text in this play. it traspases  language  barriers in such a way that any person from any country can understand it, given its universal codes.

at the theater for the new city, ny.

visit: https://bit.ly/2nfevgd to get your tickets now.

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:

it‚Äôs a way to really create the world we want to live in. 
this isn‚Äôt some fluffy say your intentions and affirmations and wait for the phone to ring kind of day.  it‚Äôs a day to write down how you want to feel in 6 months, and then ask 
what do you need to do
who do you need to be
and then go make that happen

you offer a voice that no one else has 
you offer a friendship that no one else can offer
you have a unique, god given talent that no one else has

and if you haven‚Äôt figured out what that is yet- let‚Äôs do it together.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
@jakartapac is back on stage with #blackbird , a powerful one-act play by david harrower. it tells the story of a woman confronting a man from her past, as they deal with trauma, heartbreak, and attachment. 
this play is performed as a part of the 16 film festival. with it, we hope to start a dialogue about sexual violence against women and children, and how to become a better support system for its survivors. the proceeds from this play will be donated to yayasan pulih.

you can be a part of this force of change with us!

support this play and donate now. any amount will do:
rp75k - afford us 1 hour of rehearsal time
225k - 1 day of rehearsal 
500k - 1 week of  transport and logistics
1mio - 2 weeks of water and food for cast and crews 
3mio - licensing fee to stage this play
5mio - lighting/set development

donate now by transfer to mandiri, acc. no. 1290011184773, yayasan jakarta performing arts center 
confirm your donation by sending the transfer receipt by email or whatsapp to alex (puti.rahmasari@gmail.com/ +628170770380) or
andi (personalproemail@gmail.com/ +6281314468264)

all donors will be acknowledged in the program book. donation of idr1.000k and up also will be mentioned during dialogue session and workshop. thank you!

#activismplay #performingarts #volunteerism #metoo #donateforgoodcause #speakup #changemakers #16fest

text:
de bullshit over de seksualiteit van de vrouw.

mijn creatiekracht ligt op dezelfde plek als mijn seksualiteit. zo groeit als ik cre√´er ook het verlangen om op mijn eigen manier sensueel te zijn. 
mijn seksualiteit. dus niet van jou!
dat is de eerste die naar boven komt. boosheid ofzo. alsof ik, als ik in contact ben met mijn seksualiteit opeens open ben voor bussiness en jij je daar toe mag bedienen. dan moet ik mij er ook nog voor schamen dat ik deze gevoelens bij je oproep als ik nee zeg. 1 ontmoeting waarin je ontdekt hoe machteloos je bent tegen mannelijke seksuele agressie is genoeg. ik ben jaren bang geweest voor mannen, mijn eigen seksualiteit en creatiekracht.

een laag dieper ontdek ik dat ik als vrouw natuurlijk ook verlang naar mannelijke energie. dus ja, mijn seksualiteit betekent ook dat ik jou aantrekkelijk kan vinden. het kan ook betekenen dat ik jou wil en wil dat jij naar mij verlangt. 
want man van nu, wat ben je mooi!
ik zie heel veel mooie, intelligente, warme, moedige, krachtige mannen om me heen.

ik snap dat je soms niet meer weet wat vrouwen van je willen. we lopen vaak ergens vast tussen angst, overmoedigheid, overschreeuwen en verstoppen. onpeilbaar. tijd dat we gewoon open zijn.  ik kan alleen voor mezelf spreken. 
ik draag mijn kleding en mijn lijf voor mij en mijn eigen gevoel van sensualiteit.

de man die ik het aantrekkelijkst vind, is de man die me laat merken dat hij me ziet. en dan zijn eigen controle kan houden. 'ik wil je en als je mij wil ben ik hier. ik vind je leuk en wil wel moeite doen maar dat vraagt ook dat jij een opening tot contact geeft.' zelf heb ik gekozen om mezelf met 1 man te delen. alleen zijn seksuele verlangens wil ik beantwoorden. het voelt ook goed dat het meest heilige deel van mezelf maar voor 1 man is. niet omdat het moet maar omdat ik dat kies. 
dat betekent niet dat ik je niet af en toe kan bevestigen dat ik jou ook zie en mooi vind. 
staan voor wat ik kies vraagt zelfcontrole als jij langs loopt of voor me staat met je fijne energie. toch is mijn man het waard.

ben jij je bewust van je eigen seksualiteit? durf jij daar open over te zijn naar jezelf zodat je toegang hebt tot je eigen creatiekracht?

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

text:
this picture is about an incident that happened on october 23.
.

on october 23, tamil nadu woke up to something that should've stunned it to shame. there is a village called thalavaipatti,which is located 14 kms away from the outskirts of salem near aathur. a 13 year old (8th grade) girl named rajalakshmi was beheaded by her neighbour dhinesh kumar the previous evening. she had allegedly spurned his advances. this happended when the¬†#metoo¬†campaigns were going viral,and yet nobody seemed to notice such incident.what happened was,she was sexually harassed by him previously.she even told this to her parents but they couldn't do anything as they were from a dalit family and he was from a dominant caste.that day,when chinnaponnu (rajalakshmi's mother) and rajalakshmi were stringing flowers,he came there with a sickle and beheaded her inspite of chinnaponnu's intervention.then he headed home with rajalakshmi's head where his wife sarada advised him to discard it elsewhere.subsequently, they went to police station together and surrendered.sarada convinced the police that he was mentally ill but it was just a ploy to save her husband.during investigation police made it clear that he was mentally and physically sound.they police see's this as a caste crime whereas the society see's this as a sex crime.in my opinion it's both,because he sexually assaulted her first and then he was enraged that a dalit woman had the audacity to spurn him.now he can be out on bail, which shouldn't be happening.in my opinion the case should be tried under posco act(death penalty).its a shame that we all failed to notice such a horrible incident.rape is a serious crime,i feel that the convicted rapist should experience consequences in keeping with the severity of their crime,not based on the privilege of their caste or the colour of their skin.women in india have always been worshipped as goddess and all the rapes, acid attacks and everything,all these has put us in shame.something has to be done to put an end to this cruelty.i hereby conclude that if we all join our hands together we might be able to put an end to this.¬†#justiceforrajalakshmi¬†

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
men‚Äôs studies: le blog des hommes et des masculinit√©s
christoph may ‚Äì fondateur de men‚Äôs studies
les t√©moins d‚Äôoutre-mer, francetv "we all win, if men start to questioning themselves ‚Äûhey, my name is christoph may. two years ago i started a blog on men and masculinity studies. i question manhood in a hypercritical way.

for example i ask for extreme masculinities in online culture wars or i write about the representation of tough guys like the men of steel, kylo ren or spiderman. what about the nerdy sexism in the big bang theory? why there is no #metoo-debate in hip-hip and rap? or why are more than 80 percent of all games in the gaming industry still running in combat-mode? questions like that. you know, it‚Äôs everywhere!

so i also wanna talk to the people, especially men. i do lectures on hatespeech and misogyny and i offer workhops for startups and business guys where you learn to kill your male privileges or how to question your male fantasies about flying to the mars, selfdriving cars or virtual reality porn.

and my experience shows, that all kind of men are really interested in that. they wanna get rid of their mansplaining-behaviour, they wanna be emotional daddies and take responsibility for their kids and best of all: they wanna support women and womens rights.

i think, a lot of men understood, that we all win, if men start to questioning themselves. so we just need to push that forward!

i wanna accallerate the crisis of men, cause i see it as a chance to give up power, to change your male view and finally to be a better man: positive, selfcritical and feminist.‚Äú statement by #christophmay

text:
men‚Äôs studies: le blog des hommes et des masculinit√©s
christoph may ‚Äì fondateur de men‚Äôs studies
les t√©moins d‚Äôoutre-mer, francetv "we all win, if men start to questioning themselves ‚Äûhey, my name is christoph may. two years ago i started a blog on men and masculinity studies. i question manhood in a hypercritical way.

for example i ask for extreme masculinities in online culture wars or i write about the representation of tough guys like the men of steel, kylo ren or spiderman. what about the nerdy sexism in the big bang theory? why there is no #metoo-debate in hip-hip and rap? or why are more than 80 percent of all games in the gaming industry still running in combat-mode? questions like that. you know, it‚Äôs everywhere!

so i also wanna talk to the people, especially men. i do lectures on hatespeech and misogyny and i offer workhops for startups and business guys where you learn to kill your male privileges or how to question your male fantasies about flying to the mars, selfdriving cars or virtual reality porn.

and my experience shows, that all kind of men are really interested in that. they wanna get rid of their mansplaining-behaviour, they wanna be emotional daddies and take responsibility for their kids and best of all: they wanna support women and womens rights.

i think, a lot of men understood, that we all win, if men start to questioning themselves. so we just need to push that forward!

i wanna accallerate the crisis of men, cause i see it as a chance to give up power, to change your male view and finally to be a better man: positive, selfcritical and feminist.‚Äú statement by #christophmay

text:
rehearsal process #blackbird 
#activismplay 
scared, excited,  determined, joy,  nervous,.... waves after waves of emotions putting this production together.  not only the script is hella nuanced and brilliant,  but the purpose behind the staging of this play is very close to our hearts. thus why we put our all into this. 
we are fundraising to help us finance this play.  donations are hugely appreciated.  we'll be sharing info at @jakartapac instagram. 
blackbird by david harrower is staged to instigate dialogue on sexual abuse and raise awareness.  more info follows

text:
i can't believe it's been exactly a year since i had that massive shift in energy and finally for the first time in my life felt internal peace. to finally realise the one thing that was holding me back was i didn't know who i was without all the trauma and baggage, and i then had to make the decision to unlearn everything and pretty much start again. its been one hell of a journey this year, and definitely had my fair share of challenges which i keep working my way through. happiness is everything to me, and i am trying my hardest to give life it all, and give my daughter everything she needs. i have definitely lost friends along the way but i'd much rather have very few close friends than surrounded by toxic people that thrive off dragging everyone down with their drama and negative energy. keep thriving forward is the way. i have learned many lessons on this journey, and i'm excited to see where it leads.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i will not accept what i cannot change. i will change what i cannot accept. 
i am here today, standing up for our children, for our sisters and brothers, for all victims of sexual assault, for myself. i came in protest of the judicial ruling of a man who‚Äôs name is protected by the court. after being found guilty of sexually assaulting two teenage girls on separate occasions, the ‚Äúappropriate‚Äù sentence was determined to be two weeks of jail time. one of his victims was hospitalized and left in critical condition. her physical rehabilitation took far longer than the time he will serve, let alone the emotional recovery that will last a lifetime. my heart is broken. i cannot believe this happened in my community. i cannot believe how much our judicial system has failed to protect our youth and failed to support survivors of sexual assault. 
if you share my opinion: that the judicial system should not allow people with a clear bias in favor of violent offenders to determine our fates, please sign the petition to have judge paul meyers removed from his position. i have posted the link in my bio. i encourage you to do your own research into judge meyer‚Äôs career and rulings. i ask that you please do not sign the petition based off my account alone. i do not believe in asserting power over someone‚Äôs life in a way that could negatively affect their future without merit. 
thank you for taking the time to read this. thank you to all the people who spoke so bravely today, to everyone who came out in support, and to everyone who voices support for survivors. 
#metoo #timesup

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

text:
//me too//.
.
.
.
 just the other day, scrolling through instagram, i chanced by a statement which really got me thinking about how narrow minded we as a society have grown up. while we are constantly cribbing about issues that are important to us, we are assigning a back seat to the broader picture, which potentially is more dangerous should we ever reach a level of that acute a crisis. "#metoo - said mother earth"
this statement, upon perception presents a picture of gut wrenching pathos that we've brought upon ourselves, either by wronging our home planet or maintaining an unappreciative silence instead of speaking up against them. what use is your voice of, if you don't use it against injustice? 
what we are doing is calling the attack with a spade as gardening; when what we need to do is stand up..not because it's the air that you, as an individual breathe is unclean but because in doing so, you stand up for all those that survive on unclean air and water for their entire lifetime, the number of whom, according to world statistics today is a surprising 2.5 billion ( approximately 35 percent). trees, a whooping 50% of which has been cut down by brutal inventions in the last century, literally are the source of the very thing we survive on. would you call the axeman cutting the branch he's sitting on wise? and yet humans are the most intelligent among creatures to ever exist. oh, the irony.
the society has taken a collective step back and we did nothing. strangely enough, that's where the crux of the issue lies.
this hour calls for us to stop being so self conscious and quit merely feeling sorrow. action is so much more powerful  than silent resentment, let's take each opportunity to prove so. let's stand up, united by the vision of a better tomorrow.
.
.
.
writer- rimli das

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian
