text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

"i think ("playboy") was very empowering and no one forced me to do anything," she said. "my mother taught me don't go into a hotel with a stranger, and if someone answers the door in a bathrobe and it's supposed to be a business meeting, maybe i should go with somebody else," she said. text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: this last month i checked into a rehab facility for alcohol addiction. i‚Äôve struggled many years with abusing alcohol to escape many traumatic situations, until it became necessary for me to function. i‚Äôve showed up to work, church, meetings, parties, conferences etc under the influence. i never imagined this being my reality. being a christian and a youth leader, i was ashamed, embarrassed, guilty, frustrated, afraid of what people would think, and who i would disappoint.  little did i know that leaving what i knew as ‚Äúnormal‚Äù would be the best decision i‚Äôve ever made. i would have died if i didn‚Äôt decide to go. it was the best and worst weeks of my life. addressing my addiction head on has been the hardest thing i‚Äôve ever done. however, i have never been at more peace, i have never loved myself more, and i have never been in more control of my life than i am now. i met so many people who have now become my life long friends! if you‚Äôre like me and battle the disease of addiction of any kind, i just want you to know #metoo. it‚Äôs okay to be exactly where you‚Äôre at. i just want you to know, i‚Äôm here for you, and i would love to walk through this with you. i‚Äôm not perfect, i still have a long road ahead of me but damn being sober 30 days feels amazing! i‚Äôm taking my life back 24 hours at a time! to those who have loved me through the worst parts of my addiction, thank you! to those who have loved and walked with me everyday up until now, thank you! here‚Äôs to another 30 days! #30dayssober #livingmybestlife #icanandiwill #onedayatatime #soberlife #recovery #jer2911 #metoo #addiction #staythecourse #godstrong #icandoallthings #godstilllovesme #takingmylifeback

#metoo :
it was the year 2012. i used to go to the market in the city of khandwa, where i, then stayed, always with my parents. one evening, when i was walking through the main road, an aged guy, much aged like he must have been in his late 50s or early 60s.  he was actually walking behind us for a long time. suddenly he walked past me, touched me behind and my arms as well.  it all happened like in a second's time,  but my reflex worked. i ran behind him, and even he started running. mom dad were infront of me so they couldn't see this all. but when i ran, dad and everyone around understood what could have happened. they caught the man.  and, to my relief, i slapped him twice. he exactly has spoken these words : "usne chote kapde pehena tha isiliye mujhe chadh gayi thi". and i was only wearing a knee length dress. this incident frightened me but also brought me a courage that if i fight against the wrong, they will have to weaken in their knees. like this song i played, "despacito" , i was growing to learn defending myself "slowly". ‚ù§

text:
my life has never been easy. i‚Äôve been through a lot, but everyone has. i‚Äôve been on journey to grow & heal from my childhood for the last 2 years, before that i was a mess; sad, insecure and downright mean most of the time and sometimes i still am. i build walls with most people because that‚Äôs all i‚Äôve ever been able to do to protect myself. i‚Äôve learned over the last few years that i‚Äôm way too hard on myself & set unrealistic expectations for myself, when i don‚Äôt achieve them i beat myself up for hours, days and even weeks. i over analyze and over think literally e.v.e.r.y.t.h.i.n.g. i want to be healthy; mind, body & soul but i‚Äôm still a work in progress. i was mentally & sexually abused most of my childhood and almost all the people in my life including my immediate family don‚Äôt even know because i‚Äôve always been too ashamed to say the words out loud, but i‚Äôve come to realize this is not my shame i am carrying around. i don‚Äôt want pitty or sympathy i just want people to realize not everything is as it seems. i‚Äôm still a work in progress but at least i‚Äôm trying, and i‚Äôm proud of that. 
#thecouragetoheal #workinprogess #selflove #metoo

text:
what is trauma? how does it develop? how does it affect the survivors and how can they heal?

this book will answer the questions. it's based on #vanderkolk's 30 years clinical works as a psychiatrist. i must say up front, this book is a masterpiece.

trauma isn't only experienced by the survivor of war or disaster, most of the cases are based on domestic violence and sexual abuse esp in childhood.

remember how you can't forget swimming or riding a bicycle? it's because humans have muscle memory and it happens in trauma. it shuts down the higher brain which regulates self awareness. that's why the survivors may feel immobilization (inescapable shock) and dissociation.

the conscious mind forget the details as a part of defense mechanism, but unconsciously the experience still lingers deep. people with trauma fail integrate the experience as the past. they're frozen in time. their bodies stuck within the constant state of tension and alert which may cause emotional sensitivity and health problems.

also it's possible for the survivors to not remember anything (since the trauma is repressed) until something triggers them! even though they don't remember well, they may feel uncomfortable in their own skin, not connected with anyone, or not belong in the world. they forget the details, but not the sensation. this is what we call as #ptsd.

to heal trauma we need to continue the narrative, cut the loop, and create a closure. kolk's proposed emdr therapy & neurofeedback to help the survivors remember. yes, no matter how scary, we must revisit the memory!

afterwards, we can continue with body work: yoga, theatre, dance, anything that makes us in tune with our own body! small thing like fixing our posture matters too. when we're in harmony with our body, we're in harmony with the world.

for more details you can read the excerpt above because there's a huuge amount of knowledge that i got from this book üòä kork's idea to teach emotional awareness for children (last pic) is also brilliant! definitely a must read for all psychologists, healers, and survivors out there.

text: today marks 366 days of recovery since one of the most traumatic events of my life. my self-worth and trust in others was lost, and i woke up almost every night paralyzed for quite some time. despite my trauma i am here one year later, surviving and living my life the best i can. i still have my bad days... i won't get into details on those too much because this post isn't about that. this is about recognizing that i am actively working toward recovery and even though i have had set backs along the way i am so proud of myself for how far i've come. in the past year i have done some serious self reflection and have learned to own my identity. i intend to continue to do that more day by day, in order to become the best version of me possible! here's to recovery. ‚ù§Ô∏è #metoo #recoveryisnotlinear

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

i'm just reading about the exotism of black men from slavery to modern america, first on the plantation - modern day porn. oddly, there is no real discussion about the paradigm that underscored this wicked history: white fragility, male and female
.

and first up, documented narratives of the sexual and gender diversity *among* slaves, for both men and woman, remain all but invisible; some slaves had warped (stockholm sydrome-esk) sexual affairs, love stories, etc., with their masters ...like frederick douglass (-- i know; it's fucking true. take the moment you need). the larger point is slaves were gay, trans, etc.,; sexual diversity isnt new, but you have to dig for these stories bc the (very accurate) overarching narrative was hypersexualization of slaves... but, um, where is the part about timid white girls feining a disingenuous "fear" of the black body (both male and female) to stimulate their purity in the eyes of their protector ...the proverbial master
.

it's missing leads like this that actually hold white female *humanity* back (i actually wrote about this shit in my book and it's effect on homogeneous notions of american femininity, which are basically "act like a confused child forever). i mean, it's actually white girls who have suffered the most from the absence of this narrative -- i know this shit, it's hillary clinton types who dont
.

and if we dare to unpack this (totally inauthentic) "fear" we would find a strange hybridization of fetishism, envy and posturing (a creepy as fuck) power dynamic, which is basically the makings of the *institution* of misogyny, which is then further fractioned by preformative gender ideals: the docile female plays dead before the heroic man, bc racism is just *one* of the elements that trigger the practice of the *binary construction of misogyny*, and lynching takes place
.

and all this white fragility *began* with frigidity as a signifier for class status, which is a fascinating isolated history in itself, which i could spin off on for months
.

now, i *realize* nobody else talked about this at the dinner table but my dad to my uncle's with me just around, but white girls! learn *your* fucking *history*

text:
me too post

this week! ugh this week is the week i dread and have started to fear every month. am i‚Äôm going to get hit with a migraine? how bad will it be? how many days will it last? will i have to call someone to take my boys to school? who am i inconveniencing today? how many days will i be in bed. how much pain will come this time? what plans to i have to cancel? these are the thoughts that go through my head every month right before this week hits! 
this is me last month on day 3 in bed with a migraine. this is the side that many of you don‚Äôt know or don‚Äôt have to see. this is a girl waiting for her healing, believing with all the faith in the world that it will come! i don‚Äôt post this so you can feel sorry for me, i post this because i want others to know they are not alone! for others who suffer like i do, for moms who miss their kids games because the pain is to much to bare or for those who wish people understood it‚Äôs so much worse then a headache. i‚Äôve been on the search for years now for something that would take the pain away. i‚Äôm still searching and trying a more natural approach because i just don‚Äôt want to be on a prescription medication for the rest of my life! for those of you who suffer from migraines too please post below with a me too. i want to be praying for you daily as i know others pray for me. remember you‚Äôre not alone! #migrainesuck #myhealingiscoming #metoo @echosummerhill #motherofboys #motherofachildwithadhd

text:
when will the sikh community have their own #metoo movement?
üîΩ
kaur siblings work together to prevent sexual violence and support survivors
üîΩ
while the movement‚Äôs push into the mainstream in late 2017 has led to it becoming an international front working to protect and help survivors around the world, the sikh research institute is wondering when the sikh community will have its own #metoo movement.
üîΩ
hoping to address this problem, the research institute‚Äîor sikhri for short‚Äîheld an online webinar to discuss the matter at hand. sikhri aims to strengthen bonds within the sikh community, as well as make sikh education more accessible, through courses and seminars.
üîΩ
the webinar was led by gurleen kaur, an education and prevention specialist with the violence, prevention, and response team at mit, and jasleen kaur, a researcher at sikhri. the two have been working on an article set to be released by sikhri soon, as a culminating report of their research.

text:
if you've never been raised in dysfunction, then you probably don't understand what i mean. chances are you believe poverty can be fixed by "simply going to college." you think single mothers who need assistance wouldn't be in their position if they would have just "stay of their backs or "you shouldn't have been so sexy." as if you are oblivious to the fact that there are sexual predators out here praying on women, men and children. that women or men shouldn't have a hard time coming forward to tell someone they were raped or sexually assaulted. as if these individuals aren't suffering from trauma. 
i can go on and on, but i  can see how you can think that way especially if you're never experience what it's like to grow up in poverty, where family members sexually and verbally abuse each other, where they have one or no parents usually raised by a grandparent. to look up at your elders for leadership and the answers only for them to have nothing if value to share with you other than "go to school and listen to them white folks".. what i'm saying is life is not just black and white, thus all the movement from people in the "grey" that have been at economic disadvantage and doing the best they can do to break the generational curse. 
i will elaborate more in future live youtube videos so please subscribe. thank you
